# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: balneolales
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Like all animals, humans carry vast numbers (approximately 1013 to 1014) of bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Most are in the gut, though there are many on the skin.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Most of the bacteria in and on the body are harmless or rendered so by the protective effects of the immune system, and many are beneficial, particularly the ones in the gut.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] However, several species of bacteria are pathogenic and cause infectious diseases, including cholera, syphilis, anthrax, leprosy, tuberculosis, tetanus and bubonic plague.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The most common fatal bacterial diseases are respiratory infections.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Antibiotics are used to treat bacterial infections and are also used in farming, making antibiotic resistance a growing problem.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Once regarded as plants constituting the class *Schizomycetes* ("fission fungi"), bacteria are now classified as prokaryotes.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Unlike cells of animals and other eukaryotes, bacterial cells contain circular chromosomes, do not contain a nucleus and rarely harbour membrane-bound organelles.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Although the term *bacteria* traditionally included all prokaryotes, the scientific classification changed after the discovery in the 1990s that prokaryotes consist of two very different groups of organisms that evolved from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] These evolutionary domains are called Bacteria and Archaea.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Unlike Archaea, bacteria contain ester-linked lipids in the cell membrane, possess elongation factors that are resistant to ADP-ribosylation by diphtheria toxin, use formylmethionine in protein synthesis initiation, and have numerous genetic differences, including a different 16S rRNA.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The word was first used to refer to bacteria in 1828.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Although an estimated 43,000 species of bacteria have been named, most of them have never been studied.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In fact, just 10 bacterial species account for half of all publications, whereas nearly 75% of all named bacteria have no academic research devoted to them.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The best-studied species, *Escherichia coli*, has more than 300,000 studies published on it, but many of these papers likely use it only as a cloning vehicle to study other species, without providing any insight into its own biology.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] 90% of scientific studies on bacteria focus on less than 1% of species, mostly pathogenic bacteria relevant to human health.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] While *E. coli* is probably the best-studied bacterium, a quarter of its 4000 genes are poorly studied or remain uncharacterized.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria with minimal genomes (< 600 genes, e.g.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] *Mycoplasma*) usually have a large fraction of their genes functionally characterized, given that most of them are essential and conserved in many other species.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The ancestors of bacteria were unicellular microorganisms that were the first forms of life to appear on Earth, about 4 billion years ago.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] For about 3 billion years, most organisms were microscopic, and bacteria and archaea were the dominant forms of life.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Although bacterial fossils exist, such as stromatolites, their lack of distinctive morphology prevents them from being used to examine the history of bacterial evolution, or to date the time of origin of a particular bacterial species.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] However, gene sequences can be used to reconstruct the bacterial phylogeny, and these studies indicate that bacteria diverged first from the archaeal/eukaryotic lineage.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The most recent common ancestor (MRCA) of bacteria and archaea was probably a hyperthermophile that lived about 2.5 billion–3.2 billion years ago.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The earliest life on land may have been bacteria some 3.22 billion years ago.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria were also involved in the second great evolutionary divergence, that of the archaea and eukaryotes.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Here, eukaryotes resulted from the entering of ancient bacteria into endosymbiotic associations with the ancestors of eukaryotic cells, which were themselves possibly related to the Archaea.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] This involved the engulfment by proto-eukaryotic cells of alphaproteobacterial symbionts to form either mitochondria or hydrogenosomes, which are still found in all known Eukarya (sometimes in highly reduced form, e.g. in species of amitochondrial protozoa).
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Later, some eukaryotes that already contained mitochondria also engulfed cyanobacteria-like organisms, leading to the formation of chloroplasts in algae and plants.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria are ubiquitous, living in every possible habitat on the planet including soil, underwater, deep in Earth's crust and even such extreme environments as acidic hot springs and radioactive waste.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] There are thought to be approximately 2×1030 bacteria on Earth, forming a biomass that is only exceeded by plants.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] They are abundant in lakes and oceans, in arctic ice, and geothermal springs where they provide the nutrients needed to sustain life by converting dissolved compounds, such as hydrogen sulphide and methane, to energy.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Most do not cause diseases, are beneficial to their environments, and are essential for life.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The soil is a rich source of bacteria and a few grams contain around a thousand million of them.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] They are all essential to soil ecology, breaking down toxic waste and recycling nutrients.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] They are even found in the atmosphere and one cubic metre of air holds around one hundred million bacterial cells.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The oceans and seas harbour around 3 × 1026 bacteria which provide up to 50% of the oxygen humans breathe.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Only around 2% of bacterial species have been fully studied.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria display a wide diversity of shapes and sizes.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cells are about one-tenth the size of eukaryotic cells and are typically 0.5–5.0 micrometres in length.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] However, a few species are visible to the unaided eye—for example, *Thiomargarita namibiensis* is up to half a millimetre long, *Epulopiscium fishelsoni* reaches 0.7 mm, and *Thiomargarita magnifica* can reach even 2 cm in length, which is 50 times larger than other known bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Among the smallest bacteria are members of the genus *Mycoplasma*, which measure only 0.3 micrometres, as small as the largest viruses.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria may be even smaller, but these ultramicrobacteria are not well-studied.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species are either spherical, called *cocci* (*singular coccus*, from Greek *kókkos*, grain, seed), or rod-shaped, called *bacilli* (*sing*. bacillus, from Latin *baculus*, stick).
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, called *vibrio*, are shaped like slightly curved rods or comma-shaped; others can be spiral-shaped, called *spirilla*, or tightly coiled, called *spirochaetes*.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] A small number of other unusual shapes have been described, such as star-shaped bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] This wide variety of shapes is determined by the bacterial cell wall and cytoskeleton and is important because it can influence the ability of bacteria to acquire nutrients, attach to surfaces, swim through liquids and escape predators.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species exist as single cells; others associate in characteristic patterns: *Neisseria* forms diploids (pairs), streptococci form chains, and staphylococci group together in "bunch of grapes" clusters.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can also group to form larger multicellular structures, such as the elongated filaments of *Actinomycetota* species, the aggregates of *Myxobacteria* species, and the complex hyphae of *Streptomyces* species.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] These multicellular structures are often only seen in certain conditions.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] For example, when starved of amino acids, myxobacteria detect surrounding cells in a process known as quorum sensing, migrate towards each other, and aggregate to form fruiting bodies up to 500 micrometres long and containing approximately 100,000 bacterial cells.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In these fruiting bodies, the bacteria perform separate tasks; for example, about one in ten cells migrate to the top of a fruiting body and differentiate into a specialised dormant state called a myxospore, which is more resistant to drying and other adverse environmental conditions.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often attach to surfaces and form dense aggregations called biofilms and larger formations known as microbial mats.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] These biofilms and mats can range from a few micrometres in thickness to up to half a metre in depth, and may contain multiple species of bacteria, protists and archaea.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria living in biofilms display a complex arrangement of cells and extracellular components, forming secondary structures, such as microcolonies, through which there are networks of channels to enable better diffusion of nutrients.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In natural environments, such as soil or the surfaces of plants, the majority of bacteria are bound to surfaces in biofilms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Biofilms are also important in medicine, as these structures are often present during chronic bacterial infections or in infections of implanted medical devices, and bacteria protected within biofilms are much harder to kill than individual isolated bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The bacterial cell is surrounded by a cell membrane, which is made primarily of phospholipids.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] This membrane encloses the contents of the cell and acts as a barrier to hold nutrients, proteins and other essential components within the cell.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Unlike eukaryotic cells, bacteria usually lack large membrane-bound structures in their cytoplasm such as a nucleus, mitochondria, chloroplasts and the other organelles present in eukaryotic cells.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] However, some bacteria have protein-bound organelles in the cytoplasm which compartmentalise aspects of bacterial metabolism, such as the carboxysome.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Additionally, bacteria have a multi-component cytoskeleton to control the localisation of proteins and nucleic acids within the cell, and to manage the process of cell division.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Many important biochemical reactions, such as energy generation, occur due to differences in concentration of molecules across membranes, creating a electrochemical potential analogous to a battery.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The general lack of internal membranes in bacteria means these reactions, such as electron transport, occur across the cell membrane between the cytoplasm and the outside of the cell or periplasm.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] However, in many photosynthetic bacteria, the plasma membrane is highly folded and fills most of the cell with layers of light-gathering membrane.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] These light-gathering complexes may even form lipid-enclosed structures called chlorosomes in green sulfur bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria do not have a membrane-bound nucleus, and their genetic material is typically a single circular bacterial chromosome of DNA located in the cytoplasm in an irregularly shaped body called the nucleoid.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The nucleoid contains the chromosome with its associated proteins and RNA.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Like all other organisms, bacteria contain ribosomes for the production of proteins, but the structure of the bacterial ribosome is different from that of eukaryotes and archaea.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Its translation process is also different.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria produce intracellular nutrient storage granules, such as glycogen, polyphosphate, sulfur or polyhydroxyalkanoates.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria such as the photosynthetic cyanobacteria, produce internal gas vacuoles, which they use to regulate their buoyancy, allowing them to move up or down into water layers with different light intensities and nutrient levels.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Around the outside of the cell membrane is the cell wall.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are made of peptidoglycan (also called murein), which is made from polysaccharide chains cross-linked by peptides containing D-amino acids.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are different from the cell walls of plants and fungi, which are made of cellulose and chitin, respectively.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The cell wall of bacteria is also distinct from that of archaea, which do not contain peptidoglycan.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The cell wall is essential to the survival of many bacteria, and the antibiotic penicillin (produced by a fungus called *Penicillium*) is able to kill bacteria by inhibiting a step in the synthesis of peptidoglycan.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] There are broadly speaking two different types of cell wall in bacteria, that classify bacteria into Gram-positive bacteria and Gram-negative bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The names originate from the reaction of cells to the Gram stain, a long-standing test for the classification of bacterial species.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Gram-positive bacteria possess a thick cell wall containing many layers of peptidoglycan and teichoic acids.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In contrast, Gram-negative bacteria have a relatively thin cell wall consisting of a few layers of peptidoglycan surrounded by a second lipid membrane containing lipopolysaccharides and lipoproteins.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have the Gram-negative cell wall, and only members of the *Bacillota* group and actinomycetota (previously known as the low G+C and high G+C Gram-positive bacteria, respectively) have the alternative Gram-positive arrangement.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] These differences in structure can produce differences in antibiotic susceptibility; for instance, vancomycin can kill only Gram-positive bacteria and is ineffective against Gram-negative pathogens, such as *Haemophilus influenzae* or *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria have cell wall structures that are neither classically Gram-positive or Gram-negative.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] This includes clinically important bacteria such as mycobacteria which have a thick peptidoglycan cell wall like a Gram-positive bacterium, but also a second outer layer of lipids.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In many bacteria, an S-layer of rigidly arrayed protein molecules covers the outside of the cell.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] This layer provides chemical and physical protection for the cell surface and can act as a macromolecular diffusion barrier.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] S-layers have diverse functions and are known to act as virulence factors in *Campylobacter* species and contain surface enzymes in *Bacillus stearothermophilus*.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Flagella are rigid protein structures, about 20 nanometres in diameter and up to 20 micrometres in length, that are used for motility.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Flagella are driven by the energy released by the transfer of ions down an electrochemical gradient across the cell membrane.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae (sometimes called "attachment pili") are fine filaments of protein, usually 2–10 nanometres in diameter and up to several micrometres in length.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] They are distributed over the surface of the cell, and resemble fine hairs when seen under the electron microscope.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae are believed to be involved in attachment to solid surfaces or to other cells, and are essential for the virulence of some bacterial pathogens.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Pili (*sing*. pilus) are cellular appendages, slightly larger than fimbriae, that can transfer genetic material between bacterial cells in a process called conjugation where they are called conjugation pili or sex pili (see bacterial genetics, below).
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] They can also generate movement where they are called type IV pili.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Glycocalyx is produced by many bacteria to surround their cells, and varies in structural complexity: ranging from a disorganised slime layer of extracellular polymeric substances to a highly structured capsule.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] These structures can protect cells from engulfment by eukaryotic cells such as macrophages (part of the human immune system).
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] They can also act as antigens and be involved in cell recognition, as well as aiding attachment to surfaces and the formation of biofilms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The assembly of these extracellular structures is dependent on bacterial secretion systems.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] These transfer proteins from the cytoplasm into the periplasm or into the environment around the cell.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Many types of secretion systems are known and these structures are often essential for the virulence of pathogens, so are intensively studied.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Some genera of Gram-positive bacteria, such as *Bacillus*, *Clostridium*, *Sporohalobacter*, *Anaerobacter*, and *Heliobacterium*, can form highly resistant, dormant structures called *endospores*.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Endospores develop within the cytoplasm of the cell; generally, a single endospore develops in each cell.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Each endospore contains a core of DNA and ribosomes surrounded by a cortex layer and protected by a multilayer rigid coat composed of peptidoglycan and a variety of proteins.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Endospores show no detectable metabolism and can survive extreme physical and chemical stresses, such as high levels of UV light, gamma radiation, detergents, disinfectants, heat, freezing, pressure, and desiccation.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In this dormant state, these organisms may remain viable for millions of years.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Endospores even allow bacteria to survive exposure to the vacuum and radiation of outer space, leading to the possibility that bacteria could be distributed throughout the universe by space dust, meteoroids, asteroids, comets, planetoids, or directed panspermia.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] *Clostridioides difficile* infection, a common problem in healthcare settings, is caused by spore-forming bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria exhibit an extremely wide variety of metabolic types.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The distribution of metabolic traits within a group of bacteria has traditionally been used to define their taxonomy, but these traits often do not correspond with modern genetic classifications.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolism is classified into nutritional groups on the basis of three major criteria: the source of energy, the electron donors used, and the source of carbon used for growth.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Phototrophic bacteria derive energy from light using photosynthesis, while chemotrophic bacteria breaking down chemical compounds through oxidation, driving metabolism by transferring electrons from a given electron donor to a terminal electron acceptor in a redox reaction.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Chemotrophs are further divided by the types of compounds they use to transfer electrons.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria that derive electrons from inorganic compounds such as hydrogen, carbon monoxide, or ammonia are called lithotrophs, while those that use organic compounds are called organotrophs.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Still, more specifically, aerobic organisms use oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor, while anaerobic organisms use other compounds such as nitrate, sulfate, or carbon dioxide.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria, called heterotrophs, derive their carbon from other organic carbon.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Others, such as cyanobacteria and some purple bacteria, are autotrophic, meaning they obtain cellular carbon by fixing carbon dioxide.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In unusual circumstances, the gas methane can be used by methanotrophic bacteria as both a source of electrons and a substrate for carbon anabolism.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In many ways, bacterial metabolism provides traits that are useful for ecological stability and for human society.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] For example, diazotrophs have the ability to fix nitrogen gas using the enzyme nitrogenase.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] This trait, which can be found in bacteria of most metabolic types listed above, leads to the ecologically important processes of denitrification, sulfate reduction, and acetogenesis, respectively.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolic processes are important drivers in biological responses to pollution; for example, sulfate-reducing bacteria are largely responsible for the production of the highly toxic forms of mercury (methyl- and dimethylmercury) in the environment.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Nonrespiratory anaerobes use fermentation to generate energy and reducing power, secreting metabolic by-products (such as ethanol in brewing) as waste.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Facultative anaerobes can switch between fermentation and different terminal electron acceptors depending on the environmental conditions in which they find themselves.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Unlike in multicellular organisms, increases in cell size (cell growth) and reproduction by cell division are tightly linked in unicellular organisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria grow to a fixed size and then reproduce through binary fission, a form of asexual reproduction.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Under optimal conditions, bacteria can grow and divide extremely rapidly, and some bacterial populations can double as quickly as every 17 minutes.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In cell division, two identical clone daughter cells are produced.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, while still reproducing asexually, form more complex reproductive structures that help disperse the newly formed daughter cells.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Examples include fruiting body formation by myxobacteria and aerial hyphae formation by *Streptomyces* species, or budding.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Budding involves a cell forming a protrusion that breaks away and produces a daughter cell.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In the laboratory, bacteria are usually grown using solid or liquid media.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Solid growth media, such as agar plates, are used to isolate pure cultures of a bacterial strain.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] However, liquid growth media are used when the measurement of growth or large volumes of cells are required.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Growth in stirred liquid media occurs as an even cell suspension, making the cultures easy to divide and transfer, although isolating single bacteria from liquid media is difficult.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The use of selective media (media with specific nutrients added or deficient, or with antibiotics added) can help identify specific organisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Most laboratory techniques for growing bacteria use high levels of nutrients to produce large amounts of cells cheaply and quickly.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] However, in natural environments, nutrients are limited, meaning that bacteria cannot continue to reproduce indefinitely.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] This nutrient limitation has led the evolution of different growth strategies (see r/K selection theory).
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Some organisms can grow extremely rapidly when nutrients become available, such as the formation of algal and cyanobacterial blooms that often occur in lakes during the summer.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Other organisms have adaptations to harsh environments, such as the production of multiple antibiotics by *Streptomyces* that inhibit the growth of competing microorganisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In nature, many organisms live in communities (e.g., biofilms) that may allow for increased supply of nutrients and protection from environmental stresses.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] These relationships can be essential for growth of a particular organism or group of organisms (syntrophy).
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] When a population of bacteria first enter a high-nutrient environment that allows growth, the cells need to adapt to their new environment.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The first phase of growth is the lag phase, a period of slow growth when the cells are adapting to the high-nutrient environment and preparing for fast growth.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The lag phase has high biosynthesis rates, as proteins necessary for rapid growth are produced.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The second phase of growth is the logarithmic phase, also known as the exponential phase.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The log phase is marked by rapid exponential growth.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The rate at which cells grow during this phase is known as the *growth rate* (*k*), and the time it takes the cells to double is known as the *generation time* (*g*).
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] During log phase, nutrients are metabolised at maximum speed until one of the nutrients is depleted and starts limiting growth.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The third phase of growth is the *stationary phase* and is caused by depleted nutrients.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The cells reduce their metabolic activity and consume non-essential cellular proteins.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The stationary phase is a transition from rapid growth to a stress response state and there is increased expression of genes involved in DNA repair, antioxidant metabolism and nutrient transport.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The final phase is the death phase where the bacteria run out of nutrients and die.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] There are many exceptions to this; for example, some *Streptomyces* and *Borrelia* species contain a single linear chromosome, while some bacteria including species of *Vibrio* contain more than one chromosome.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria contain plasmids, small extra-chromosomal molecules of DNA that may contain genes for various useful functions such as antibiotic resistance, metabolic capabilities, or various virulence factors.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Whether they have a single chromosome or more than one, almost all bacteria have a haploid genome.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] This means that they have only one copy of each gene encoding proteins.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] This is in contrast to eukaryotes, which are diploid or polyploid, meaning they have two or more copies of each gene.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] This means that unlike humans, who may still be able to create a protein if the gene becomes mutated (since the human genome has an extra copy in each cell), a bacterium will be completely unable to create the protein if its gene incurs an inactivating mutation.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacterial genomes usually encode a few hundred to a few thousand genes.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The genes in bacterial genomes are usually a single continuous stretch of DNA.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Although several different types of introns do exist in bacteria, these are much rarer than in eukaryotes.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria, as asexual organisms, inherit an identical copy of the parent's genome and are clonal.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] However, all bacteria can evolve by selection on changes to their genetic material DNA caused by genetic recombination or mutations.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Mutations arise from errors made during the replication of DNA or from exposure to mutagens.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Mutation rates vary widely among different species of bacteria and even among different clones of a single species of bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Genetic changes in bacterial genomes emerge from either random mutation during replication or "stress-directed mutation", where genes involved in a particular growth-limiting process have an increased mutation rate.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria transfer genetic material between cells.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] First, bacteria can take up exogenous DNA from their environment in a process called transformation.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria can naturally take up DNA from the environment, while others must be chemically altered in order to induce them to take up DNA.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The development of competence in nature is usually associated with stressful environmental conditions and seems to be an adaptation for facilitating repair of DNA damage in recipient cells.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Second, bacteriophages can integrate into the bacterial chromosome, introducing foreign DNA in a process known as transduction.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Many types of bacteriophage exist; some infect and lyse their host bacteria, while others insert into the bacterial chromosome.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Third, bacteria can transfer genetic material through direct cell contact via conjugation.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In such cases, gene acquisition from other bacteria or the environment is called horizontal gene transfer and may be common under natural conditions.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria are motile (able to move themselves) and do so using a variety of mechanisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The best studied of these are flagella, long filaments that are turned by a motor at the base to generate propeller-like movement.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The bacterial flagellum is made of about 20 proteins, with approximately another 30 proteins required for its regulation and assembly.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The flagellum is a rotating structure driven by a reversible motor at the base that uses the electrochemical gradient across the membrane for power.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can use flagella in different ways to generate different kinds of movement.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria (such as *E. coli*) have two distinct modes of movement: forward movement (swimming) and tumbling.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The tumbling allows them to reorient and makes their movement a three-dimensional random walk.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The flagella of a group of bacteria, the spirochaetes, are found between two membranes in the periplasmic space.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] They have a distinctive helical body that twists about as it moves.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Two other types of bacterial motion are called twitching motility that relies on a structure called the type IV pilus, and gliding motility, that uses other mechanisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In twitching motility, the rod-like pilus extends out from the cell, binds some substrate, and then retracts, pulling the cell forward.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Motile bacteria are attracted or repelled by certain stimuli in behaviours called *taxes*: these include chemotaxis, phototaxis, energy taxis, and magnetotaxis.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] In one peculiar group, the myxobacteria, individual bacteria move together to form waves of cells that then differentiate to form fruiting bodies containing spores.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The myxobacteria move only when on solid surfaces, unlike *E. coli*, which is motile in liquid or solid media.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Several *Listeria* and *Shigella* species move inside host cells by usurping the cytoskeleton, which is normally used to move organelles inside the cell.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] By promoting actin polymerisation at one pole of their cells, they can form a kind of tail that pushes them through the host cell's cytoplasm.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] A few bacteria have chemical systems that generate light.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] This bioluminescence often occurs in bacteria that live in association with fish, and the light probably serves to attract fish or other large animals.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often function as multicellular aggregates known as biofilms, exchanging a variety of molecular signals for intercell communication and engaging in coordinated multicellular behaviour.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The communal benefits of multicellular cooperation include a cellular division of labour, accessing resources that cannot effectively be used by single cells, collectively defending against antagonists, and optimising population survival by differentiating into distinct cell types.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] For example, bacteria in biofilms can have more than five hundred times the increased resistance to antibacterial agents than individual "planktonic" bacteria of the same species.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] One type of intercellular communication by a molecular signal is called quorum sensing.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing determines whether the local population is dense enough to support investment in processes that are only successful if large numbers of similar organisms behave similarly, such as excreting digestive enzymes or emitting light.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing enables bacteria to coordinate gene expression and to produce, release, and detect autoinducers or pheromones that accumulate with the growth in cell population.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Classification seeks to describe the diversity of bacterial species by naming and grouping organisms based on similarities.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can be classified on the basis of cell structure, cellular metabolism or on differences in cell components, such as DNA, fatty acids, pigments, antigens and quinones.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] While these schemes allowed the identification and classification of **bacterial strains**, it was unclear whether these differences represented variation between distinct species or between strains of the same species.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] This uncertainty was due to the lack of distinctive structures in most bacteria, as well as lateral gene transfer between unrelated species.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Due to lateral gene transfer, some closely related bacteria can have very different morphologies and metabolisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Classification of bacteria is determined by publication in the International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology, and Bergey's Manual of Systematic Bacteriology.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The International Committee on Systematic Bacteriology (ICSB) maintains international rules for the naming of bacteria and taxonomic categories and for the ranking of them in the International Code of Nomenclature of Bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Historically, bacteria were considered a part of the Plantae, the plant kingdom, and were called "Schizomycetes" (fission-fungi).
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] For this reason, collective bacteria and other microorganisms in a host are often called "flora".
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The term "bacteria" was traditionally applied to all microscopic, single-cell prokaryotes.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] However, molecular systematics showed prokaryotic life to consist of two separate domains, originally called Eubacteria and Archaebacteria, but now called Bacteria and Archaea that evolved independently from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The archaea and eukaryotes are more closely related to each other than either is to the bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] These two domains, along with Eukarya, are the basis of the three-domain system, which is currently the most widely used classification system in microbiology.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] However, due to the relatively recent introduction of molecular systematics and a rapid increase in the number of genome sequences that are available, bacterial classification remains a changing and expanding field.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] For example, Cavalier-Smith argued that the Archaea and Eukaryotes evolved from Gram-positive bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The identification of bacteria in the laboratory is particularly relevant in medicine, where the correct treatment is determined by the bacterial species causing an infection.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Consequently, the need to identify human pathogens was a major impetus for the development of techniques to identify bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Once a pathogenic organism has been isolated, it can be further characterised by its morphology, growth patterns (such as aerobic or anaerobic growth), patterns of hemolysis, and staining.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The *Gram stain*, developed in 1884 by Hans Christian Gram, characterises bacteria based on the structural characteristics of their cell walls.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The thick layers of peptidoglycan in the "Gram-positive" cell wall stain purple, while the thin "Gram-negative" cell wall appears pink.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] By combining morphology and Gram-staining, most bacteria can be classified as belonging to one of four groups (Gram-positive cocci, Gram-positive bacilli, Gram-negative cocci and Gram-negative bacilli).
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Some organisms are best identified by stains other than the Gram stain, particularly mycobacteria or *Nocardia*, which show acid fastness on Ziehl–Neelsen or similar stains.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Culture techniques are designed to promote the growth and identify particular bacteria while restricting the growth of the other bacteria in the sample.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Often these techniques are designed for specific specimens; for example, a sputum sample will be treated to identify organisms that cause pneumonia, while stool specimens are cultured on selective media to identify organisms that cause diarrhea while preventing growth of non-pathogenic bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Specimens that are normally sterile, such as blood, urine or spinal fluid, are cultured under conditions designed to grow all possible organisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Other organisms may need to be identified by their growth in special media, or by other techniques, such as serology.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] As with bacterial classification, identification of bacteria is increasingly using molecular methods, and mass spectroscopy.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have not been characterised and there are many species that cannot be grown in the laboratory.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Diagnostics using DNA-based tools, such as polymerase chain reaction, are increasingly popular due to their specificity and speed, compared to culture-based methods.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] These methods also allow the detection and identification of "viable but nonculturable" cells that are metabolically active but non-dividing.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] The main way to characterize and classify these bacteria is to isolate their DNA from environmental samples and mass-sequence them.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] This approach has identified thousands, if not millions of candidate species.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p01] Based on some estimates, more than 43,000 species of bacteria have been described, but attempts to estimate the true number of bacterial diversity have ranged from 107 to 109 total species—and even these diverse estimates may be off by many orders of magnitude.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Despite their apparent simplicity, bacteria can form complex associations with other organisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] These symbiotic associations can be divided into parasitism, mutualism and commensalism.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] The word "commensalism" is derived from the word "commensal", meaning "eating at the same table" and all plants and animals are colonised by commensal bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] In humans and other animals, trillions of them live on the skin, the airways, the gut and other orifices.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Referred to as "normal flora", or "commensals", these bacteria usually cause no harm but may occasionally invade other sites of the body and cause infection.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] *Escherichia coli* is a commensal in the human gut but can cause urinary tract infections.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Similarly, streptococci, which are part of the normal flora of the human mouth, can cause heart disease.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Some species of bacteria kill and then consume other microorganisms; these species are called *predatory bacteria*.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] These include organisms such as *Myxococcus xanthus*, which forms swarms of cells that kill and digest any bacteria they encounter.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Other bacterial predators either attach to their prey in order to digest them and absorb nutrients or invade another cell and multiply inside the cytosol.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] These predatory bacteria are thought to have evolved from saprophages that consumed dead microorganisms, through adaptations that allowed them to entrap and kill other organisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Certain bacteria form close spatial associations that are essential for their survival.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] One such mutualistic association, called interspecies hydrogen transfer, occurs between clusters of anaerobic bacteria that consume organic acids, such as butyric acid or propionic acid, and produce hydrogen, and methanogenic archaea that consume hydrogen.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] The bacteria in this association are unable to consume the organic acids as this reaction produces hydrogen that accumulates in their surroundings.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Only the intimate association with the hydrogen-consuming archaea keeps the hydrogen concentration low enough to allow the bacteria to grow.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] In soil, microorganisms that reside in the rhizosphere (a zone that includes the root surface and the soil that adheres to the root after gentle shaking) carry out nitrogen fixation, converting nitrogen gas to nitrogenous compounds.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] This serves to provide an easily absorbable form of nitrogen for many plants, which cannot fix nitrogen themselves.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Many other bacteria are found as symbionts in humans and other organisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] The presence of this gut flora also inhibits the growth of potentially pathogenic bacteria (usually through competitive exclusion) and these beneficial bacteria are consequently sold as probiotic dietary supplements.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Nearly all animal life is dependent on bacteria for survival as only bacteria and some archaea possess the genes and enzymes necessary to synthesise vitamin B12, also known as cobalamin, and provide it through the food chain.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Vitamin B12 is a water-soluble vitamin that is involved in the metabolism of every cell of the human body.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] It is a cofactor in DNA synthesis and in both fatty acid and amino acid metabolism.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] It is particularly important in the normal functioning of the nervous system via its role in the synthesis of myelin.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] The body is continually exposed to many species of bacteria, including beneficial commensals, which grow on the skin and mucous membranes, and saprophytes, which grow mainly in the soil and in decaying matter.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] The blood and tissue fluids contain nutrients sufficient to sustain the growth of many bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] The body has defence mechanisms that enable it to resist microbial invasion of its tissues and give it a natural immunity or innate resistance against many microorganisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Unlike some viruses, bacteria evolve relatively slowly so many bacterial diseases also occur in other animals.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] If bacteria form a parasitic association with other organisms, they are classed as pathogens.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] A pathogenic cause for a known medical disease may only be discovered many years later, as was the case with *Helicobacter pylori* and peptic ulcer disease.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Bacterial diseases are also important in agriculture, and bacteria cause leaf spot, fire blight and wilts in plants, as well as Johne's disease, mastitis, salmonella and anthrax in farm animals.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Each species of pathogen has a characteristic spectrum of interactions with its human hosts.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Some organisms, such as *Staphylococcus* or *Streptococcus*, can cause skin infections, pneumonia, meningitis and sepsis, a systemic inflammatory response producing shock, massive vasodilation and death.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Yet these organisms are also part of the normal human flora and usually exist on the skin or in the nose without causing any disease at all.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Other organisms invariably cause disease in humans, such as *Rickettsia*, which are obligate intracellular parasites able to grow and reproduce only within the cells of other organisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] One species of *Rickettsia* causes typhus, while another causes Rocky Mountain spotted fever.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] *Chlamydia*, another phylum of obligate intracellular parasites, contains species that can cause pneumonia or urinary tract infection and may be involved in coronary heart disease.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Some species, such as *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, *Burkholderia cenocepacia*, and *Mycobacterium avium*, are opportunistic pathogens and cause disease mainly in people who are immunosuppressed or have cystic fibrosis.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Some bacteria produce toxins, which cause diseases.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] These are endotoxins, which come from broken bacterial cells, and exotoxins, which are produced by bacteria and released into the environment.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] The bacterium *Clostridium botulinum* for example, produces a powerful exotoxin that cause respiratory paralysis, and *Salmonellae* produce an endotoxin that causes gastroenteritis.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Some exotoxins can be converted to toxoids, which are used as vaccines to prevent the disease.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Bacterial infections may be treated with antibiotics, which are classified as bacteriocidal if they kill bacteria or bacteriostatic if they just prevent bacterial growth.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] There are many types of antibiotics, and each class inhibits a process that is different in the pathogen from that found in the host.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] An example of how antibiotics produce selective toxicity are chloramphenicol and puromycin, which inhibit the bacterial ribosome, but not the structurally different eukaryotic ribosome.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Antibiotics are used both in treating human disease and in intensive farming to promote animal growth, where they may be contributing to the rapid development of antibiotic resistance in bacterial populations.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Infections can be prevented by antiseptic measures such as sterilising the skin prior to piercing it with the needle of a syringe, and by proper care of indwelling catheters.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Surgical and dental instruments are also sterilised to prevent contamination by bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Disinfectants such as bleach are used to kill bacteria or other pathogens on surfaces to prevent contamination and further reduce the risk of infection.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Bacteria, often lactic acid bacteria, such as *Lactobacillus* species and *Lactococcus* species, in combination with yeasts and moulds, have been used for thousands of years in the preparation of fermented foods, such as cheese, pickles, soy sauce, sauerkraut, vinegar, wine, and yogurt.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] The ability of bacteria to degrade a variety of organic compounds is remarkable and has been used in waste processing and bioremediation.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Bacteria capable of digesting the hydrocarbons in petroleum are often used to clean up oil spills.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Fertiliser was added to some of the beaches in Prince William Sound in an attempt to promote the growth of these naturally occurring bacteria after the 1989 *Exxon Valdez* oil spill.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] These efforts were effective on beaches that were not too thickly covered in oil.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Bacteria are also used for the bioremediation of industrial toxic wastes.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] In the chemical industry, bacteria are most important in the production of enantiomerically pure chemicals for use as pharmaceuticals or agrichemicals.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Bacteria can also be used in place of pesticides in biological pest control.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] This commonly involves *Bacillus thuringiensis* (also called BT), a Gram-positive, soil-dwelling bacterium.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Subspecies of this bacteria are used as Lepidopteran-specific insecticides under trade names such as Dipel and Thuricide.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Because of their specificity, these pesticides are regarded as environmentally friendly, with little or no effect on humans, wildlife, pollinators, and most other beneficial insects.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Because of their ability to quickly grow and the relative ease with which they can be manipulated, bacteria are the workhorses for the fields of molecular biology, genetics, and biochemistry.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] By making mutations in bacterial DNA and examining the resulting phenotypes, scientists can determine the function of genes, enzymes, and metabolic pathways in bacteria, then apply this knowledge to more complex organisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] This aim of understanding the biochemistry of a cell reaches its most complex expression in the synthesis of huge amounts of enzyme kinetic and gene expression data into mathematical models of entire organisms.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] This is achievable in some well-studied bacteria, with models of *Escherichia coli* metabolism now being produced and tested.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] This understanding of bacterial metabolism and genetics allows the use of biotechnology to bioengineer bacteria for the production of therapeutic proteins, such as insulin, growth factors, or antibodies.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Because of their importance for research in general, samples of bacterial strains are isolated and preserved in Biological Resource Centres.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] This ensures the availability of the strain to scientists worldwide.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were first observed by the Dutch microscopist Antonie van Leeuwenhoek in 1676, using a single-lens microscope of his own design.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Leeuwenhoek did not recognize bacteria as a distinct category of microorganisms, referring to all microorganisms that he observed, including bacteria, protists, and microscopic animals, as animalcules.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] He published his observations in a series of letters to the Royal Society of London.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were Leeuwenhoek's most remarkable microscopic discovery.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Their size was just at the limit of what his simple lenses could resolve, and, in one of the most striking hiatuses in the history of science, no one else would see them again for over a century.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] His observations also included protozoans, and his findings were looked at again in the light of the more recent findings of cell theory.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg introduced the word "bacterium" in 1828.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] In fact, his *Bacterium* was a genus that contained non-spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria, as opposed to *Bacillus*, a genus of spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria defined by Ehrenberg in 1835.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Louis Pasteur demonstrated in 1859 that the growth of microorganisms causes the fermentation process and that this growth is not due to spontaneous generation (yeasts and molds, commonly associated with fermentation, are not bacteria, but rather fungi).
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Along with his contemporary Robert Koch, Pasteur was an early advocate of the germ theory of disease.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Before them, Ignaz Semmelweis and Joseph Lister had realised the importance of sanitised hands in medical work.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Semmelweis, who in the 1840s formulated his rules for handwashing in the hospital, prior to the advent of germ theory, attributed disease to "decomposing animal organic matter".
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] His ideas were rejected and his book on the topic condemned by the medical community.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] After Lister, however, doctors started sanitising their hands in the 1870s.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Robert Koch, a pioneer in medical microbiology, worked on cholera, anthrax and tuberculosis.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] In his research into tuberculosis, Koch finally proved the germ theory, for which he received a Nobel Prize in 1905.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] In Koch's postulates, he set out criteria to test if an organism is the cause of a disease, and these postulates are still used today.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Ferdinand Cohn is said to be a founder of bacteriology, studying bacteria from 1870.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Cohn was the first to classify bacteria based on their morphology.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Though it was known in the nineteenth century that bacteria are the cause of many diseases, no effective antibacterial treatments were available.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] In 1910, Paul Ehrlich developed the first antibiotic, by changing dyes that selectively stained *Treponema pallidum*—the spirochaete that causes syphilis—into compounds that selectively killed the pathogen.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] Ehrlich, who had been awarded a 1908 Nobel Prize for his work on immunology, pioneered the use of stains to detect and identify bacteria, with his work being the basis of the Gram stain and the Ziehl–Neelsen stain.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] A major step forward in the study of bacteria came in 1977 when Carl Woese recognised that archaea have a separate line of evolutionary descent from bacteria.
[src:balneolales/bacteria-p02] This new phylogenetic taxonomy depended on the sequencing of 16S ribosomal RNA and divided prokaryotes into two evolutionary domains, as part of the three-domain system.
[src:balneolales/balneolaceae] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] The **Genome Taxonomy Database** (GTDB) is an online database that maintains information on a proposed nomenclature of prokaryotes, following a phylogenomic approach based on a set of conserved single-copy proteins.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] In addition to resolving paraphyletic groups, this method also reassigns taxonomic ranks algorithmically, updating names in both cases.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] Information for archaea was added in 2020, along with a species classification based on average nucleotide identity.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] Each update incorporates new genomes as well as automated and manual curation of the taxonomy.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] An open-source tool called GTDB-Tk is available to classify draft genomes into the GTDB hierarchy.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] The GTDB system, via GTDB-Tk, has been used to catalogue not-yet-named bacteria in the human gut microbiome and other metagenomic sources.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] The GTDB is incorporated into the *Bergey's Manual of Systematics of Archaea and Bacteria* in 2019 as its phylogenomic resource.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] The genomes used to construct the phylogeny are obtained from NCBI (RefSeq and Genbank), and GTDB releases are indexed to RefSeq releases, starting with release 76.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] Importantly and increasingly, this dataset includes draft genomes of uncultured microorganisms obtained from metagenomes and single cells, ensuring improved genomic representation of the microbial world.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] All genomes are independently quality controlled using CheckM before inclusion in GTDB.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] Genomes first undergo gene calling to extract genes.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] The taxonomy is based on trees inferred with FastTree from an aligned concatenated set of 120 single copy marker proteins for Bacteria under a WAG model, and with IQ-TREE from a concatenated set of 53 (since RS207; 122 before) marker proteins for Archaea under the PMSF model.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] Additional marker sets are also used to cross-validate tree topologies including concatenated ribosomal proteins and ribosomal RNA genes.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] The *relative evolutionary divergence* (RED) metric, which determines the taxonomic ranks used, is derived from the two main trees by the PhyloRank program.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] Species are delimited using average nucleotide identity and alignment fraction, both calculated by *skani*.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] For species existing in a previous release, GTDB compares the quality and position of two genomes and may decide to switch to a new *species representative* genome.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] GTDB personnel curates the taxonomy from the aforementioned sources by checking them against the results of PhyloRank and the tree.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] For the each new taxon, the curators try to find a proposed name in literature for it.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] If there is no name proposed, the taxon is given a placeholder name by adding a suffix to the original name, e.g.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] The web interface displays a tree based on the taxonomy (not the entire Newick file), down to the genome assembly level.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] Each genome assembly has a page detailing its metadata and a history of how it's classified in each GTDB release.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] GTDB "has now become an important resource for prokaryotic taxonomy".
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] Both its species tree and elements of its methodology are used by taxonomists to improve the current, accepted taxonomy under the *Prokaryotic Code*.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] For example, a taxonomist may make references to the GTDB tree on top of their own phylogenetic tree to further support a taxonomic proposal.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] There has been even more ambitious proposals to import large parts of the database into the accepted taxonomy.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] A 2022 article in the IJSEM, written by third-party authors, proposes to assign names based on meaningless Latin syllable to over 65 thousand GTDB taxa, though none of these names have made their way into the LPSN.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] A 2023 article by the GTDB team proposes to import 223 higher-order taxa into the *Prokaryotic Code* system and 49 under the *SeqCode* system.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] Many of the names published under the *Prokaryotic Code* have already been validated.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] Unlike other bacteria, cyanobacteria are governed by a separate nomenclature code, the *Botanical Code* (ICNafp), and has a rich collection of taxa described morphologically, before the advent of molecular methods.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] Considerable work has been done at the higher taxonomical ranks (orders and families) to harmonize them with the results of molecular phylogeny, but problematic taxa remain at the lower levels.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] One representative example is the genus *Synechococcus* (and the broader Synechococcales), where distantly-related taxa remain lumped together.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] A 2020 article proposed using GTDB's methods to split this taxon into five orders, but it did not make an effect on the accepted taxonomy as the names were not validly published.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] The *Botanical Code* treats names validly published under the *Prokaryotic Code* as valid, but the converse was not true until 2022, when the *Prokaryotic Code* reciprocated.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] Using some cyanobacterial genera names published under the *Botanical Code*, the aforementioned 2023 GTDB article proposed 10 cyanobacterial higher taxa to be accepted under the *Prokrayotic Code*.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] The cyanobacterial community revised its higher-level taxa in 2023 independently of the GTDB, making use of a combination of phylogenomic and 16S trees.
[src:balneolales/genome-taxonomy-database] More broadly, the nomenclatural situation of cyanobacteria remains disordered enough to cause several confusing assignments in GTDB requiring manual adjustment.
[src:balneolales/global-biodiversity-information-facility] The **Global Biodiversity Information Facility** (**GBIF**) is an international organisation that focuses on making scientific data on biodiversity available via the Internet using web services.
[src:balneolales/global-biodiversity-information-facility] The data are provided by many institutions from around the world; GBIF's information architecture makes these data accessible and searchable through a single portal.
[src:balneolales/global-biodiversity-information-facility] Data available through the GBIF portal are primarily distribution data on plants, animals, fungi, and microbes for the world, and scientific names data.
[src:balneolales/global-biodiversity-information-facility] The mission of the GBIF is to facilitate free and open access to biodiversity data worldwide to underpin sustainable development.
[src:balneolales/global-biodiversity-information-facility] GBIF strives to form informatics linkages among digital data resources from across the spectrum of biological organisation, from genes to ecosystems, and to connect these to issues important to science, society and sustainability by using georeferencing and GIS tools.
[src:balneolales/global-biodiversity-information-facility] It works in partnership with other international organisations such as the Catalogue of Life partnership, Biodiversity Information Standards, the Consortium for the Barcode of Life (CBOL), the Encyclopedia of Life (EOL), and GEOSS.
[src:balneolales/global-biodiversity-information-facility] The biodiversity data available through the GBIF has increased by more than 1,150% in the past decade, partially due to the participation of citizen scientists.
[src:balneolales/global-biodiversity-information-facility] From 2002 to 2014, GBIF awarded a prestigious annual global award in the area of biodiversity informatics, the Ebbe Nielsen Prize, valued at €30,000.
[src:balneolales/global-biodiversity-information-facility] As of 2018, the GBIF Secretariat presents two annual prizes: the GBIF Ebbe Nielsen Challenge and the Young Researchers Award.
[src:balneolales/interim-register-of-marine-and-nonmarine-genera] IRMNG can be queried online for access to the latest version of the dataset and is also made available as periodic snapshots or data dumps for import/upload into other systems as desired.
[src:balneolales/interim-register-of-marine-and-nonmarine-genera] The database was commenced in 2006 at the then CSIRO Division of Marine and Atmospheric Research in Australia and, since 2016, has been hosted at the Flanders Marine Institute (VLIZ) in Belgium.
[src:balneolales/interim-register-of-marine-and-nonmarine-genera] The database aspires to provide complete coverage of both accepted and unaccepted genus names across all kingdoms, with a subset only of species names included as a secondary activity.
[src:balneolales/interim-register-of-marine-and-nonmarine-genera] IRMNG content can be queried and displayed freely via the web, and download files of the data down to the taxonomic rank of genus as at specific dates are available in the Darwin Core Archive (DwC-A) format.
[src:balneolales/interim-register-of-marine-and-nonmarine-genera] The data include homonyms (with their authorities), including both available (validly published) and selected unavailable names.
[src:balneolales/interim-register-of-marine-and-nonmarine-genera] IRMNG was initiated and designed by Australian biologist and data manager Tony Rees in 2006.
[src:balneolales/interim-register-of-marine-and-nonmarine-genera] For his work on this and other projects, GBIF awarded him the 2014 Ebbe Nielsen Prize.
[src:balneolales/interim-register-of-marine-and-nonmarine-genera] From 2006 to 2014 IRMNG was located at CSIRO Marine and Atmospheric Research, and was moved to the Flanders Marine Institute (VLIZ) over the period 2014–2016; from 2016 onwards all releases have been available via its new website www.irmng.org which is hosted by VLIZ.
[src:balneolales/interim-register-of-marine-and-nonmarine-genera] VLIZ also hosts the World Register of Marine Species (WoRMS), using a common infrastructure.
[src:balneolales/interim-register-of-marine-and-nonmarine-genera] From 2018 onwards, IRMNG data are also being used to populate the taxonomic hierarchy and provide generic names for a range of taxa in the areas of protists (kingdoms Protozoa and Chromista) and plant algae (Charophyta, Chlorophyta, Glaucophyta and Rhodophyta) in the Catalogue of Life.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The **National Center for Biotechnology Information** (**NCBI**) is part of the National Library of Medicine (NLM), a branch of the National Institutes of Health (NIH).
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] It is approved and funded by the government of the United States.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The NCBI is located in Bethesda, Maryland, and was founded in 1988 through legislation sponsored by US Congressman Claude Pepper.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The NCBI houses a series of databases relevant to biotechnology and biomedicine and is an important resource for bioinformatics tools and services.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Major databases include GenBank for DNA sequences and PubMed, a bibliographic database for biomedical literature.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Other databases include the NCBI Epigenomics database.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] All these databases are available online through the Entrez search engine.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] NCBI was directed by David Lipman, one of the original authors of the BLAST sequence alignment program and a widely respected figure in bioinformatics.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] These inconsistencies created roadblocks for researchers utilizing multiple databases in tandem in their studies, as related information in different databases was difficult to integrate and made using information from one database as evidence to explain information in another database difficult.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] This led the NLM to propose the creation of the NCBI to lead the standardization between biotechnology databases to promote easier retrieval of information by users and allow interlinking of databases for study.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The proposal for NCBI also sought for it to act as a storage repository and distribution center for biotechnology information, as well as a developer of information analysis tools.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Congressman Claude Pepper, an advocate for medical research, introduced multiple bills to Congress between 1986 and 1988 proposing the creation of the NCBI before the proposal was approved on November 4, 1988, establishing the NCBI within the NLM.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] In 1990, a team at NCBI including mathematician Stephen Altschul developed the BLAST tool for comparing biological sequences, building upon the preexisting FASTA program.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The NCBI also assumed responsibility for the preexisting GenBank database of DNA and amino acid sequences, initially allowing internet access through email in 1992.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] In 1994, the NCBI established a website to allow easier online access to their services, namely the BLAST tool, the GenBank database, and the Entrez retrieval system for searching biomedical databases.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The NCBI would later go on in 2000 to host access to the human genome, mapped by the Human Genome Project, as well as PubMed Central, a free online archive of biomedical literature from scientific journals.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The US Congress would later mandate in 2008 that papers resulting from research provided by NIH funding featured in scientific journals be made available publicly on PubMed within 12 months of publication, further broadening the articles hosted.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The NCBI website provides a wide range of databases and tools for Biomedical and genomic research.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] A complete list of available resources can be found on the All-Resources page.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The NCBI Bookshelf stands as a freely accessible digital repository which provides researchers and educators and the public with access to biomedical books and documents.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The repository is maintained by the National Center for Biotechnology Information which supports wide dissemination of scientific knowledge.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The Bookshelf contains multiple publication types including textbooks and clinical manuals and guidelines and monographs.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] These resources are contributed by government agencies and academic institutions and scientific publishers which ensures reliability and relevance to the biomedical field.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Access to the NCBI Bookshelf is provided through the NCBI web interface which allows users to search and navigate filters across integrated biomedical databases.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The interface incorporates search functionalities which support keyword queries and filtering for efficient information retrieval.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The integration of the Bookshelf with other NCBI resources stands as a key strength which enables navigation between scientific literature and biological data.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Entries may be linked to related records in PubMed and Gene databases which enhances accessibility and research productivity.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Publishers may submit materials to the Bookshelf through a structured process which requires scientific accuracy and peer review and relevance to biomedical topics.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Accepted materials undergo standardized formatting and metadata indexing which facilitates efficient searching and cross-referencing.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The NCBI Bookshelf plays an important role in supporting education and clinical practice and research because it provides free access to high-quality scientific literature.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] This availability encourages evidence-based decision making and contributes to knowledge dissemination and research advancement within the global biomedical community.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] BLAST (Basic Local Alignment Search Tool) is an algorithm and suite of programs used to perform sequence similarity searches between a query sequence and sequences in a selected database, such as GenBank.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] It is commonly used to compare nucleotide and protein sequences by identifying regions of local similarity.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] BLAST operates by using heuristic methods, taking shortcuts in order to reach an answer faster.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] BLAST has to read in a user-inputted query sequence then the sequence from the selected database and search parameters.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] It then analyzes the query sequence for low complexity and repeats within this sequence in order to produce a set of characters that’ll be used to compare the query sequence to sequences within the database.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] First, the database searches for short matching sequences using the character set, which are then extended, not allowing gaps to find initial alignments.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] If these gap free alignments reach a certain score threshold, they are used to begin a gapped extension that estimates the alignment's score and length without yet calculating insertions or deletions, which are more computationally expensive.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] In order to avoid a computationally expensive process, only gapped alignments that meet a specified score are kept, with lower scored alignments being discarded.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Finally, BLAST performs traceback, meaning the retained alignments are fully extended again, this time including insertions and deletions as well as more sensitive parameters to produce the final, detailed alignments.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Input sequences are typically provided in FASTA or GenBank format, and results can be returned in multiple formats including HTML, XML, and plain text.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The default output from the webpage presents results in table format, along with graphs of matched sequences in a separate tab, statistical significance values, and detailed alignments between the query and subject sequences.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] There are multiple BLAST programs available through the NCBI BLAST homepage, which differ in the types of sequences they analyze.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The Image below displays one such program, blastp, displaying the interface's general layout.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The Entrez Global Query Cross-Database Search System is used at NCBI for all the major databases such as Nucleotide and Protein Sequences, Protein Structures, PubMed, Taxonomy, Complete Genomes, OMIM, and several others.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Entrez is both an indexing and retrieval system having data from various sources for biomedical research.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] NCBI distributed the first version of Entrez in 1991, composed of nucleotide sequences from PDB and GenBank, protein sequences from SWISS-PROT, translated GenBank, PIR, PRF, PDB, and associated abstracts and citations from PubMed.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Entrez is specially designed to integrate the data from several different sources, databases, and formats into a uniform information model and retrieval system which can efficiently retrieve that relevant references, sequences, and structures.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] NCBI hosts many different databases associated with Biotechnology Information, Ranging from chemical compounds to gene and protein sequences.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] GenBank is the NIH genetic sequence database, an annotated collection of all publicly available DNA sequences.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Database resources have been maintained by NCBI since 1992 when the organization had responsibility for making available the GenBank DNA sequence database.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] GenBank coordinates with individual laboratories and other sequence databases, such as those of the European Molecular Biology Laboratory (EMBL) and the DNA Data Bank of Japan (DDBJ).
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Since 1992, NCBI has grown to provide other databases in addition to GenBank.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The database Gene is a collection of characterization and organized information about genes.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] It serves as a major node in the nexus of the genomic map, expression, sequence, protein function, structure, and homology data.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] A unique GeneID is assigned to each gene record that can be followed through revision cycles.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Gene records for known or predicted genes are established here and are demarcated by map positions or nucleotide sequences.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Gene has several advantages over its predecessor, LocusLink, including, better integration with other databases in NCBI, broader taxonomic scope, and enhanced options for query and retrieval provided by the Entrez system.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The database Protein is a collection of text record for individual protein sequences, derived from many different resources such as NCBI Reference Sequence (RefSeq) project, GenBank, PDB, and UniProtKB/SWISS-Prot.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Protein records are present in different formats including FASTA and XML and are linked to other NCBI resources.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] Protein provides the relevant data to the users such as genes, DNA/RNA sequences, biological pathways, expression and variation data, and literature.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] It also provides the predetermined sets of similar and identical proteins for each sequence as computed by the BLAST.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The Structure database of NCBI contains 3D coordinate sets for experimentally determined structures in PDB that are imported by NCBI.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The Conserved Domain database (CDD) of protein contains sequence profiles that characterize highly conserved domains within protein sequences.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] It also has records from external resources like SMART and Pfam.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] There is another database of proteins known as Protein Clusters database, which contains sets of proteins sequences that are clustered according to the maximum alignments between the individual sequences as calculated by BLAST.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The PubChem database of NCBI is a public resource for molecules and their activities against biological assays.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] PubChem is searchable and accessible by Entrez information retrieval system.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The data stored in both the BioAssay and the Compound databases describes data from PubChem's Substance database.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The NCBI assigns a unique identifier (taxonomy ID number) to each species of organism.
[src:balneolales/national-center-for-biotechnology-information] The NCBI has software tools that are available through web browsers or by File Transfer Protocol (FTP).
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] The synonymous name "Hydrobacteria" (hydro = "water") refers to the moist environment inferred for the common ancestor of those species.
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] In contrast, species of Bacillati possess adaptations for life on land.
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] Since 2024, the only validly published name for this group is kingdom Pseudomonadati (there used to be none, because no levels above phylum could exist in earlier versions of the Prokaryotic Code).
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] "Gracilicutes," which was described in 1978 by Gibbons and Murray, is sometimes used in place of Pseudomonadati.
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] However, "Gracilicutes" included Cyanobacteria (a member of Bacillati) and was not constructed under the now generally accepted three-domain system.
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] More recently, a redefinition of "Gracilicutes" was proposed but it did not include a molecular phylogeny or statistical analyses.
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] Also, it did not follow the three-domain system, claiming instead that the lineage of eukaryotes + Archaea is nested within Bacteria as a close relative of Actinomycetota, a tree not supported in any molecular phylogeny.
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] Pseudomonadati and Bacillati were inferred to have diverged approximately 3 billion years ago, suggesting that land (continents) had been colonized by prokaryotes at that time.
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] They include these superphyla and phyla: Acidobacteriota, Aquificota, Bdellovibrionota, Campylobacterota, Deferribacterota, Dependentiae, Desulfobacterota, Desulfuromonadota, Elusimicrobiota, FCB superphylum, Myxococcota, Nitrospirota, Proteobacteria, PVC superphylum, and Spirochaetota.
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] Some unrooted molecular phylogenetic analyses have not supported this dichotomy of Bacillati and Pseudomonadati, but the most recent genomic analyses, including those that have focused on rooting the tree, have found these two groups to be monophyletic.
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] Together, Pseudomonadati and Bacillati form a large clade containing 97% of prokaryotes and 99% of all species of Bacteria known by 2009, and placed by Battistuzzi and Hedges in the proposed taxon Selabacteria, in allusion to their phototrophic abilities (Greek σέλας = light).
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] Currently, the bacterial phyla that are outside of Pseudomonadati + Bacillati, and thus justifying the taxon Selabacteria, are debated and may or may not include Fusobacteria.
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] The definition of two major divisions within the domain Bacteria, Pseudomonadati, and Bacillati, has come largely from rooted phylogenetic analyses of genomes.
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] Unrooted analyses have not fully supported this division, drawing attention to the importance of rooted trees of life.
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] The two recent analyses of bacterial phylogeny both supported the division of Pseudomonadati and Bacillati.
[src:balneolales/pseudomonadati] However, they interpreted the evolution of the cell wall differently, with one concluding that the last common ancestor of Bacteria was a monoderm (gram-positive bacteria) and the other concluding that it was a diderm (gram-negative bacteria).
